<tree expanded="true" show-heading="true" show-metadata="true" toc="false" root="false"><frontmatter> <anchor>208</anchor>  <taxon>Definition</taxon> <addr>axt-000Q</addr>  <route>axt-000Q.xml</route> <date><year>2023</year> <month>9</month> <day>15</day></date> <authors><author>James R. Munkres</author> </authors> <title>Hausdorff space (point-set)</title> </frontmatter> <mainmatter><p>  A space <tex>X</tex> is called <em>Hausdorff</em> if for any two distinct points <tex>x_1,
  x_2  \in  X</tex>, there exist a <em>disjoint</em> pair of open neighbourhoods <tex>U_1, U_2
   \in   \mathcal{O} ( X )</tex>, of <tex>x_1</tex> and <tex>x_2</tex>.
</p><p>  Adapted from <link href="munkres-topology-2000.xml" type="local" title="Topology by Munkres">Topology by Munkres</link>.
</p></mainmatter> <backmatter><contributions/> <context/> <related/> <backlinks><tree expanded="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="true" toc="false" root="false"><frontmatter> <anchor>209</anchor>  <taxon>Theorem</taxon> <addr>axt-000X</addr>  <route>axt-000X.xml</route> <date><year>2023</year> <month>9</month> <day>15</day></date>  <title>Hausdorff property and filter bases</title> </frontmatter> <mainmatter><p>  A space <tex>X</tex> is <link href="axt-000Q.xml" type="local" title="Hausdorff">Hausdorff</link> iff every <link href="axt-000Y.xml" type="local" title="Filter base">filter base</link> has at
